stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: Password Stealing Files Submitted for Analysis
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description: On 14 August 2013, several files were submitted for analysis. The first is an HTML page with embedded hyperlinks. The second set of files are password stealing trojans that call out to several command and control (C2) domains to post information and download additional malicious files.

stix:Indicator.indicator:Description: "aggiornamento.html" is an online payment form where it asks users to input the following: cardholder's name, fiscal code, number of paper and expiration. A hyperlink is embedded in the html.

"Scan‐001‐08132013.exe" is custom packed. It uses "PEncrypt" which is a software protection utility. The strings located in the executable's .RES SECTION indicates that the malware is capable of stealing stored account information and credentials used in installed applications such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), email, and Internet browsers. It gathers directory lists, passwords, port numbers, server names, user names, and browser certificates by retrieving addresses of Windows APIs, checks if WOW64 is running, obtains volume GUID path, generates a CLSID using the format string "%08X‐%04X‐%04X‐%02X%02X‐%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X".
Finally, it collects OS and other relevant information. The malware code also revealed the presence of one URI string. Further analysis is needed to determine functionality and the purpose of its use. The URI string is: 2http://www.facebook.com/
The process, "cmd.exe" is created in the "%WINDIR%/System32" directory. Its purpose is to execute and delete the batch file,"[random numbers].bat". The batch file is located in the "%USERPROFILE%\Local Settings\Temp" directory.
"Scan‐001‐08132013.exe" made attempts to connect to remote websites via port 80 to request files via "HTTP GET". The remote sites and requested files are: http://Missionsearchjobs.com/D5F7G.exe http://betterbacksystems.com/kvq.exe http://www.printdirectadvertising.com/vfMJH.exe http://S381195155.onlinehome.us/vmkCQg8N.exe
Once the malware, "Scan‐001‐08132013.exe", gathers the required information, it communicates with a remote site to send the information via HTTP POST. There were attempted connections made to remote sites via port 80. The payload that was sent to the remote sites are encoded with a length of 275 bytes.

"Scan_001.exe" is a copy of "Scan‐001‐08132013.exe". Both files have the same network, file and behavior indicators.

This batch file was created by the malware in the %TEMP% directory. Its purpose is to delete the loader files, "Scan‐001‐08132013.exe" and "Scan_001.exe", once it complete execution. The process, "cmd.exe" deletes the loader files. The syntax of the batch file is: 
		

	 :ktk 


 del 	 %1 
	if 		 exist 	 %1 	 goto 	 ktk
 del 	 %0
This same file was utilized in phishing campaigns outlined in IB-13-10533 and IB-13-10332.

This domain is hard-coded into the file "aggiornamento.html" (MD5: 225da1516f1a48910907be0383a9b813). aggiornamento.html, which is an online payment form, utilizes several files from this domain such as:
